Analysis of the Target Image  
Looking closely at the finished model, it uses exactly four blocks in three “layers”:  
•  Layer 1 (bottom): Two identical red arch‐shaped blocks set side by side. From the front, you see the half‐circle openings.  
•  Layer 2 (middle): A single yellow rectangular block laid horizontally, bridging across the two red arches.  
•  Layer 3 (top): One yellow half‐cylinder block resting on the center (or slightly toward one end) of the yellow rectangular block.  

Selecting Blocks from the Dictionary  

1)  Red Arch Blocks (two needed)  
   – From the dictionary images, the red arch with its opening running “front‐to‐back” is block #1.  
   – Because both base arches in the target are oriented the same way, you will use block #1 twice.  

2)  Yellow Rectangular Block (one needed)  
   – The long yellow rectangular piece, oriented lengthwise left‐to‐right, matches dictionary block #8.  

3)  Yellow Half‐Cylinder (one needed)  
   – The half‐cylindrical yellow piece with the curved top is block #11.  

Hence the required blocks (by index) are:  
•  #1 (twice)  
•  #8 (once)  
•  #11 (once)  

Assembly Order  
Below is a simple step‐by‐step sequence using the exact dictionary indices:

{  
  Step1: Move block with index 1  
  Step2: Move block with index 1  
  Step3: Move block with index 8  
  Step4: Move block with index 11  
}
